 <td style="vertical-align:top; padding-left:5px">
 
 <div id="wikiheader">
 
 <span style="font-size:120%;font-weight:bold">Build_Index</span>
 &nbsp;
 <div> 
 
 <i>Building the index.</i>
 
 
 
 <div id="wikiauthor" style="float:right">
 Updated <span title="Sat May 26 12:55:25 2012">
 Today (6 hours ago)</span>
 
 by <a style="white-space: nowrap" href="http://code.google.com/u/115835183135888412771/">drcy...@gmail.com</a>
 
 </div>
 </div>
 </div>
 
 <div id="wikicontent">
 <div class="vt" id="wikimaincol">
 <p><ul><li><a href="Build_Index#Introduction">Introduction</a></li><li><a href="Build_Index#What_are_the_indices_needed?">What are the indices needed?</a></li><li><a href="Build_Index#Creating_the_indexes">Creating the indexes</a></li><li><a href="Build_Index#Suggested_way_to_build_the_reverse_FM_index">Suggested way to build the reverse FM index</a></li><li><a href="Build_Index#SOLiD_index">SOLiD index</a></li><li><a href="Build_Index#Automating_the_task">Automating the task</a></li><li><a href="Build_Index#Command_line_parameters">Command line parameters</a></li></ul> </p><h1><a name="Introduction"></a>Introduction<a href="Build_Index#Introduction" class="section_anchor"></a></h1><p>This is an introduction to the indices needed by BatMis and how to build them. </p><h1><a name="What_are_the_indices_needed?"></a>What are the indices needed?<a href="Build_Index#What_are_the_indices_needed?" class="section_anchor"></a></h1><p>We need to create two sets of indices for a given genome, one is the FM index of the genome, and the other is the FM index of the reverse string of the genome. We  replace &quot;don&#x27;t cares&quot;(&#x27;n&#x27; and &#x27;N&#x27;) with the base &#x27;c&#x27;. Each FM index will have two files with extensions <tt>.bwt</tt> and <tt>.fmv</tt>. During the creation of FM indices, several other auxiliary files will be output. We need files with extensions <tt>.sa</tt>, at least for the reverse string of the genome, to decode the mapping results. Another file with the extension <tt>.ann.location</tt> will be created if the reference genome is made out of combining several genomes. </p><h1><a name="Creating_the_indexes"></a>Creating the indexes<a href="Build_Index#Creating_the_indexes" class="section_anchor"></a></h1><p>Given a FASTA file, <tt>bwtdbformat</tt> will create its FM index and some other auxiliary files. In order to assist in creating the reverse index of a genome, several scripts and utilities have been included. The Perl script <tt>strip.pl</tt> will build a file consisting only of nucleotides in a FASTA file, and will strip other information. The binary executable <tt>reverse</tt> will reverse any file. </p><h1><a name="Suggested_way_to_build_the_reverse_FM_index"></a>Suggested way to build the reverse FM index<a href="Build_Index#Suggested_way_to_build_the_reverse_FM_index" class="section_anchor"></a></h1><p>We can first strip the genome FASTA file and save it, say as <tt>genome.bin</tt>. We can then use the reverse program to reverse <tt>genome.bin</tt>, and then add a header &#x27;&gt;&#x27; to indicate that the resulting file is in FASTA format. Finally, we can replace all the don&#x27;t cares in the resulting file with &#x27;c&#x27; using the Linux command <tt>tr</tt>. Finally we can run <tt>bwtdbformat</tt> to build the indices.  </p><h1><a name="SOLiD_index"></a>SOLiD index<a href="Build_Index#SOLiD_index" class="section_anchor"></a></h1><p>First translate all the bases to uppercase bases A,C,G,T. The script <tt>filter.pl</tt> will do this. The format of the command if <tt>filter.pl input_file translate_file&#x27;.To use a genome for SOLiD mapping, we must convert it to colorspace with the script </tt>b2c.pl<tt>. The format of the command is </tt>b2c.pl GENOME<tt>, which will create a colorspace converted fasta file  </tt>GENOME.cfq<tt>. This file should now be used, instead of </tt>GENOME` file, when building the index. An example session of building the color index for <tt>genome.fa</tt> is: </p><pre class="prettyprint">./filter.pl genome.fa genomeC.fa
./b2c.pl genomeC.fa genomeC
./build_index genomeC</pre><h1><a name="Automating_the_task"></a>Automating the task<a href="Build_Index#Automating_the_task" class="section_anchor"></a></h1><p>We have included a shell script that will automate the creation of the required files out of a genome file. To build an index for ILLUMINA mapping, invoke the script with the command  </p><p><tt>build_index GENOME illumina &lt;path&gt;</tt> </p><p>The script will replace uncalled bases in the reference with the nucleotide &#x27;c&#x27;. To replace them with a random nucleotide use the command </p><p><tt>build_index GENOME random &lt;path&gt;</tt> </p><p>where <tt>GENOME</tt> is the name of the FASTA file, and the script will output the files related to an index on <tt>&lt;path&gt;</tt>. If <tt>&lt;path&gt;</tt> is not specified, the files will be created in the folder containing<tt>GENOME</tt>. </p><p>To auto build the colorspace index, use the command </p><p><tt>build_index GENOME color &lt;path&gt;</tt> </p><p>The colorspace index will be built with the base name GENOMEC. </p><h1><a name="Command_line_parameters"></a>Command line parameters<a href="Build_Index#Command_line_parameters" class="section_anchor"></a></h1><p>Format of <tt>strip.pl</tt> is </p><p><tt>strip.pl file1 file2</tt> </p><p>where <tt>file1</tt> is the FASTA file to be striped, and <tt>file2</tt> is the resulting file. </p><p>Format of <tt>reverse</tt> is </p><p><tt>reverse -b number -i filename1 -o filename2</tt> </p><p>where <tt>number</tt> is an integer indicating the size of buffer used, <tt>filename1</tt> is the file to be reversed, and <tt>filename2</tt> is the result. </p><p>  </p>
 </div>
 </div>
 </td><tr>
</table>
